    "D. Thermal expectation valuesWe will compare the time-averages of expectation values ⟨ Ô(t)⟩ in the steady state to thermal expectation values in the canonical ensemble.",
    "The thermal expectation value of the energy isE = tr[ρ Ĥ],(18)where ρ is the statistical operatorρ = 1 Z tr[e -β Ĥ].",
    "(19)Here, β = 1/T is the inverse temperature (we set k B = 1) and Z is the partition function.Assuming thermalization [62,63], the expected temperature is obtained by equating the energy in the initial state to the thermal expectation value:E 0 = ⟨Ψ 0 | Ĥ|Ψ 0 ⟩ = tr[ρ Ĥ].",
    "(20)The thermal expectation value of a given observable compatible with the initial energy E 0 is then given by⟨ Ô⟩ T = tr[ρ Ô].",
    "(21) E. Short-time evolutionIt is instructive to determine the short-time evolution analytically."
